  Functional Coverage - Method 1: The Basics & Triggering

  ### 1. Code Coverage vs. Functional Coverage

  • What it is:
      • Code Coverage is calculated automatically by the simulator. It literally just checks, "Did the simulator execute line 42 of your code?"
      • Functional Coverage is written manually by you. It checks, "Did my random testbench actually generate a VIP packet and send it to Address 0?"
  • Why it is used: Code coverage might be 100% (every line of code was executed), but if you forgot to write the code for a specific feature, Code
  Coverage won't know! We use Functional Coverage to guarantee that our random values hit all the rules in the design specification.

  ### 2. Covergroups and Coverpoints

  • What it is:
      • A  covergroup  is a custom block of code. Think of it as a physical Clipboard with a Checklist.
      • A  coverpoint  goes inside the covergroup. Think of it as a Specific Question on that checklist (e.g., "Did variable  a  hit the value 3?").
  • Where it is used: A covergroup can be written in 3 places:
      1. Inside a  class  (Most common)
      2. Inside a  module
      3. Outside entirely
  • Syntax:
    covergroup my_checklist;
      question_1 : coverpoint my_variable;
    endgroup
    Important: Just like a class, writing the  covergroup  only creates the blueprint. You MUST use  new()  to build it in memory (e.g.,  my_checklist =
  new(); ).

  ### 3. Triggering a Covergroup

  • What it is: The simulator does not check your variables constantly. You have to tell it exactly when to look at the variables and tick the boxes on
  the checklist.
  • How it is used: There are 3 ways to trigger it:
      1. Manual Trigger: Calling the built-in  .sample()  function in your code.
      2. Clock Edge: Telling the covergroup to trigger automatically on a clock tick:  covergroup cg @(posedge clk);
      3. Event: Telling the covergroup to trigger when an event happens:  covergroup cg @(my_event.triggered);


 Here is the Golden Rule of SystemVerilog Covergroups:

  • If you write the covergroup inside a class, it is permanently locked to that class. You MUST build its memory from inside that class (which is why we
  always put it inside  function new() ). If you go out to the module and try to type  pkt.cg = new(); , the simulator will reject it.
  • If you write the covergroup outside in a module, then you must build its memory outside in the module.

  Basically: You must build the memory in the exact same place where you wrote the covergroup!



   Functional Coverage - Method 2: Conditions, Control, & Cross Coverage

  In Method 1, our checklist was very basic. It just tracked every single number that was generated. But in real verification, we want our checklists to
  be smart. We want them to only track things under specific conditions.

  ### 1. Conditional Coverage ( iff  keyword)

  • What it is: A rule that tells the coverpoint to completely ignore values unless a specific condition is true. ( iff  stands for "if and only if").
  • Why it is used: Imagine a memory chip with an  address  variable and an  enable  pin. If the  enable  pin is  0 , the memory is turned off. We
  absolutely do not care what the  address  is when the chip is turned off! So, we tell the coverpoint to only track the address  iff (enable == 1) .
  • Syntax:
   coverpoint variable_name iff (condition);

  ### 2. System Control ( start  and  stop  functions)

  • What they are: Built-in functions that act like a "Pause" and "Play" button for your entire covergroup.
  • Why it is used: To save simulation time! If you have hit 100% coverage, there is no reason to keep checking the boxes on the clipboard. You can write
  an  if  statement in your code: "If coverage == 100, then call  .stop()  to pause the checklist."
  • Syntax:
   cg_inst.stop();  or  cg_inst.start();

  ### 3. Cross Coverage (Guaranteed Interview Question)

  • What it is: Instead of tracking variables independently, Cross Coverage tracks the combination of two or more coverpoints at the exact same time.
  • Why it is used: Let's look at a problem:
      • You have a coverpoint for Address (0, 1, 2, 3). You hit all of them. (Coverage = 100%)
      • You have a coverpoint for Action (READ, WRITE). You hit both of them. (Coverage = 100%)
      • The Problem: Did you ever test a WRITE to Address 3? You don't know! You tested Address 3, and you tested Write, but maybe never at the same
      time!
      • The Solution: You  cross  the two coverpoints together to track every single possible combination (e.g., Read-0, Write-0, Read-1, Write-1...).
  • Syntax:
   cross coverpoint_1, coverpoint_2;


  Functional Coverage - Method 3: Bins (Explicit, Ignore, and Illegal)

  ### What exactly is a "Bin"?

  Let's go back to our parking lot analogy. If a  coverpoint  is a column on your clipboard (like "Car Colors"), a Bin is a specific checkbox inside that
  column (like Checkbox 1: Red, Checkbox 2: Blue).
  Every time your randomizer generates a number, the simulator drops a tally mark into the correct bin.

  ### 1. Automatic Bins (Implicit Bins)

  • What it is: If you don't write any bins yourself, the simulator automatically creates one bin for every single possible value.
  • The Problem: If your variable is a 32-bit address, there are 4 billion possible numbers. If you use Automatic Bins, your computer will try to create
  4 billion checkboxes and it will run out of memory!
      • Note: By default, the simulator limits automatic bins to 64. You can change this using  option.auto_bin_max , which we will cover later!


  ### 2. Explicit Bins (Manual Bins)

  • What it is: Instead of letting the simulator create a bin for everything, you explicitly tell it exactly which numbers you care about.
  • Why it is used: "I have a 32-bit address, but I am only testing Address 10 and Address 20 today. Only give me coverage percentages for those two
  numbers."
  • Syntax:  bins bin_name = {value};  or  bins bin_name = {[range]};

  ### 3. Ignore Bins ( ignore_bins )

  • What it is: A bin that tells the simulator to completely ignore specific values.
  • Why it is used: Let's say you have a 2-bit variable (0, 1, 2, 3), but your hardware is physically incapable of processing the number  3 . You tell
  the simulator to  ignore_bins bad_num = {3}; . Now, the total coverage math is only calculated out of 3 bins instead of 4!

  ### 4. Illegal Bins ( illegal_bins )

  • What it is: The most powerful debugging bin. If the simulator hits an illegal bin, it immediately crashes the simulation and prints a Fatal Error.
  • Why it is used: Imagine a State Machine. State 0 is Idle, State 1 is Run. If the State variable somehow becomes  99 , your hardware is critically
  broken! You put  99  in an illegal bin to instantly catch the bug.
