 ### 3. "Why are you using  .sample()  two times? One time is enough, na?"

  No, one time is NOT enough! This is a very important rule in SystemVerilog.
  Think of  .sample()  like a camera shutter button.
  If you randomize variables 10 times, the variables change 10 times. But if you only click  .sample()  once at the very end, the simulator only takes
  one picture and misses the other 9 numbers!
  Rule: Every single time you generate new random numbers, you MUST press the shutter button ( .sample() ) to record those new numbers.

  ### 4. "Bin means we are checking coverage for a particular value, that's it?"

  YES! EXACTLY. That is the perfect definition.
  If you don't write any bins, the simulator checks the coverage for every single number in the world.
  By writing  bins b1 = {2}; , you are saying: "I only care about checking the coverage for the number 2. I don't care about anything else."


   Functional Coverage - Method 4: Transitions, Wildcards, & Options

  ### 1. Transition Bins ( => )

  • What it is: Instead of checking if a single number happened, a Transition Bin checks if a sequence of numbers happened in exact order over time.
  • Why it is used: To test State Machines! For example, a traffic light. You don't just want to know if the light turned Green (1), Yellow (2), and Red
  (3). You need to prove that it went exactly  1 -> 2 -> 3 . If it goes  1 -> 3 , that is a bug!
  • Syntax:  bins my_sequence = (1 => 2 => 3);

  ### 2. Wildcard Bins ( wildcard bins )

  • What it is: A bin that uses the  ?  character to say "I don't care what this specific bit is."
  • Why it is used: Imagine a 4-bit binary number  (1001) . You want to test if the top two bits are  11 . You don't care what the bottom two bits are.
  Instead of writing out every single combination ( 1100 ,  1101 ,  1110 ,  1111 ), you just use wildcards!
  • Syntax:  wildcard bins top_bits = {4'b11??};  (This single bin automatically accepts 12, 13, 14, and 15).

  ### 3. Coverage Options ( option. )

  • What it is: Special commands you write inside the covergroup that change how the simulator calculates the math. We already used one! ( option.
  per_instance = 1 ). Here are the other important ones:
      1.  option.at_least = 5;  (The most common one!)
          • Normally, if a bin is hit one time, the simulator checks the box and says "100% Covered". By setting  at_least = 5 , you are telling the
          simulator: "Do NOT check this box until the randomizer generates this number 5 times!"
      2.  option.auto_bin_max = 10;
          • If you don't write explicit bins, the simulator creates "Automatic Bins". To prevent your computer from running out of memory on a 32-bit
          variable, you limit it. "Only create 10 automatic bins maximum."



 ### 1. The Transition Bin Syntax

  You asked for the exact syntax for transition bins. Here is how it is built:
   bins <bin_name> = (<value1> => <value2>);

  The  =>  symbol is called the Transition Operator. You can literally read it out loud in English as "followed by on the next sample".

  •  bins state_test = (0 => 1);
      • Read this as: "I want to track if the state was  0 , followed by the state being  1  on the very next  .sample() ."


  ### 2. Deep Dive:  option.per_instance = 1;

  In SystemVerilog, you can create 100 different  Packet  objects ( pkt1 ,  pkt2 ...  pkt100 ).

  • Without this line: The simulator is lazy. It takes the checklists from all 100 packets, mashes them together into one giant pile, and only gives you
  one "Global Score". It is impossible to ask, "What is the score for just  pkt1 ?"
  • With this line:  per_instance  means "Calculate the math for each individual object." Now, the simulator gives every single packet its own private
  checklist. You can ask for  pkt1.cg.get_inst_coverage()  and it will give you the exact score for just that one packet.
  (Note: We almost ALWAYS use this line in the industry!)

  ### 3. Deep Dive:  option.at_least = 3;

  This changes the math of how you reach 100%.

  • Without this line: If a number drops into a bin just 1 time, the simulator checks the box and says "Great, 100% Covered!"
  • With this line: You are being more strict. If the number drops into the bin 1 time, the simulator says "Not good enough, that's only 33% covered." If
  it hits 2 times, it says "66% covered." It will not check the box and say "100% Covered" until that specific number drops into the bin 3 times. It is
  used when you want to heavily stress-test a specific value multiple times.
